25|$|Houghton Mifflin's {{abridged}} English translation {{left out}} some of Hitler's more antisemitic and militaristic statements. This motivated Alan Cranston, an <b>American</b> reporter <b>for</b> <b>United</b> Press International in Germany (and later a U.S. Senator from California), to publish his own abridged and annotated translation. Cranston believed this version more accurately reflected {{the contents of the}} book and Hitler's intentions. In 1939, Cranston was sued by Hitler's publisher for copyright infringement, and a Connecticut judge ruled in Hitler's favour. By the time the publication of Cranston's version was stopped, 500,000 copies had already been sold. Today, the profits and proceeds are given to various charities.|$|R
